# /etc/passwd

- fundamental config file that stores info about user accounts
- world-readable, but only the root user can modify
- Passwords are stored in /etc/shadow, not /etc/passwd

## Breakdown of fields

1. username
2. password (x or * indicated encrypted password in /etc/shadow)
3. UID
4. GID (corresponds to the user’s primary group in /etc/group)
5. GECOS (comment or full name)
6. home_directory (path to user’s home directory)
7. shell (user’s login shell (e.g., /bin/bash, /bin/false)

# /etc/shadow

- critical security file that stores encrypted (hashed) passwords and related password-aging information for user accounts
- complements /etc/passwd
- only the root user (or processes with elevated privileges) can read it

## Breakdown of fields

1. username
2. password (encrypted password hash or a special value like ! or *)
    1. `!` (account locked)
    2. `*`  (account cannot be logged into (no valid password))
    3. Blank (no password required)
    4. `$id$salt$hash` (encrypted password hash) ($id indicates algorithm used)
    5. Common hash identifiers
        1. `$1$` MD5
        2. `$2a$`, `$2b$`, `$2y$` Blowfish (bcrypt)
        3. `$5$` SHA-256
        4. `$6$` SHA-512
3. last_change (when the password was last changed)
4. min (minimum number of days before the password can be changed)
5. max (maximum number of days before the password must be changed)
6. warn (number of days before expiration to warn the users)
7. inactive (days after password expires until the account is disabled)
8. expire (date when the account expires)
9. reserved (reserved for future use (usually empty)

# /etc/group

- defines groups on the system - collection of users that share permissions and privileges
- used by the OS to determine which users belong to which groups, controlling access to files, devices, and proecsses
- stores information about all user groups
- each line corresponds to one group definition
- used along with /etc/passwd to manage user permissions

# Breakdown of fields

1. group_name (the name of the group)
2. password (optional group password, usually x or empty, real passwords stored in /etc/gshadow)
3. GID (group id)
4. user_list (comma-separated list of users that are members of the group)

| GID | Group name |
| --- | --- |
| 0 | root |
| 27 | sudo |

## Managing Groups

View all groups 

```bash
cat /etc/group
```

View groups for a user

```bash
groups <username>
```

Add a new group

```bash
sudo groupadd <group_name>
```

# /etc/gshadow

- secure companion to /etc/group
- stores encrypted group passwords and detailed group administration information
- Ensures only privileged processes (like groupadd, gpasswd, or usermod) can modify or view sensitive group data
- used by the system when verifying group membership or managing shared access
- only the root user and certain system processes can read or modify it

## Breakdown of fields

1. group_name
2. password (encrypted group password (or a special symbol). ususually unused (`!` or `*`)
3. administrators (comma-separated list of users who can manage the group (add/remove members)
4. members (comma-separated list of users who are members of the group

## Password Field Values

- `!` locked group (cannot use password to join)
- `*` no password set / disabled
- Blank - Group has no password (security risk)
- $id$salt$hash

## Managing /etc/gshadow

Set or change the group’s password

```bash
sudo gpasswd groupname
```

Add a user to a group

```bash
sudo gpasswd -a user groupname
```

Remove a user from a group

```bash
sudo gpasswd -d user groupname
```

Set a user as group administrator

```bash
sudo gpasswd -A user groupname
```

Verify consistency between /etc/group 

```bash
sudo grpck
```

# adduser

- add a user to the system
- Install the adduser package in ubuntu, debian, mint distros
    
    ```bash
    sudo apt install adduser
    ```
    
- Install adduser on a system using dnf (like Fedora, Rocky Linux, AlmaLinux)
    
    ```bash
    sudo dnf install shadow-utils
    ```
    
- Add a new user (interactive mode)
    
    ```bash
    adduser <username>
    ```
    
    - Creates new user
    - Creates home directory
    - Prompts for a password
    - Prompts for user details
    - Adds default groups
- Add user with a different shell
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser <username> --shell /bin/zsh
    ```
    
- Add a user with a different configuration file
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser <username> --conf custom_config.conf
    ```
    
- Add a user with different home directory
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser <username> --home /home/other-home-directory/
    ```
    
- Get version of the adduser command
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --version
    ```
    
- Display the help section of the adduser command
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser -h
    ```
    
- Non-interactive User Creation for user (for scripts)
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --disabled-password --gecos "" <username>
    ```
    
- Add user with custom UID/GID
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --uid <custom UID> --gid <custom GID> <username>
    ```
    
- Disable Password Login for user (e.g., for SSH key only)
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --disabled-password <username>
    ```
    
- Add an existing user to a specific group
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser <username> <groupname>
    ```
    
- Add a user without a Home Directory
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --no-create-home <username>
    ```
    
- Add a System User
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser --system <username>
    ```
    
    - creates a system account (UID < 1000 typically)
    - No password login
    - Used for services or daemons

# addgroup

- add group to the system
- `addgroup`  primarily associated with Debian/Ubuntu
- `groupadd` used by CentOS and other RHEL-based distros
- Basic syntax
    
    ```bash
    sudo addgroup [options] <groupname>
    ```
    

- Install addgroup package
    
    ```bash
    sudo apt install addgroup
    ```
    
- Add a new group
    
    ```bash
    sudo addgroup <groupname>
    ```
    
- Create a system group
    
    ```bash
    sudo addgroup --system <name>
    ```
    
    - Create a system group (with a lower GID, typically < 1000) for daemons/services
- Add an existing user to a group
    
    ```bash
    sudo adduser <username> <groupname>
    ```
    
- View group information
    
    ```bash
    getent group <groupname>
    ```
    
    or
    
    ```bash
    grep <groupname> /etc/group
    ```

# deluser

- remove a user from the system
- basic syntax
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser [options] <username>
    ```
    
- Delete a user account and keep Home Directory
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser <username>
    ```
    
- Delete a user and their home directory
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser --remove-home <username>
    ```
    
- Remove a user and all associated files
    
    ```bash
    sudo seluser --remove-all-files <username>
    ```
    
- Remove a user from a specific group
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser <username> <groupname>
    ```
    
- Delete user account even while the user is logged in
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser --force <username>
    ```
    
- Delete user account and backup the Home Directory
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser --backup-to /backup_dir <username>
    ```
    
- View verbose mode of removing a user
    
    ```bash
    sudo deluser --verbose <username>
    ```

# delgroup

- remove a group from the system
- basic syntax
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup [options] <groupname>
    ```
    
- remove a group from the system
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup <groupname>
    ```
    
- delete a system group
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup --system <name>
    ```
    
- View verbose mode
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup --verbose <groupname>
    ```
    
- Simulate group deletion
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup --dry-run <groupname>
    ```
    
- Delete a group used by a system user
    
    ```bash
    sudo delgroup --only-if-empty <groupname>
    ```
    
- Check if group exists before deletion
    
    ```bash
    getent group <groupname> && sudo delgroup <groupname>
    ```
    
- View help options
    
    ```bash
    delgroup --help
    ```
